    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-03-09T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-03-09T12:00:00-05:00" n="1182"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1182">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">767.68119/3–945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-09T19:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 9, 1945—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>331. The Yugoslav Ambassador<note n="1" xml:id="d1182fn1">Iliya
                        Shumenkovich.</note> informed me today that he had learned from a reliable
                    source that subsequent to the Yalta Conference,<note n="2" xml:id="d1182fn2">The
                        Yalta Conference between President Roosevelt, British Prime Minister
                        Churchill, and Chairman of the Council of People’s Commissars of the Soviet
                        Union Stalin met February 4–February 11, 1945; see <ref
                            target="frus1945Malta">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Conferences at Malta and
                            Yalta, 1945</ref>.</note> Molotov<note n="3" xml:id="d1182fn3"
                        >Vyacheslav Mikhailovich Molotov, People’s Commissar for Foreign Affairs of
                        the Soviet Union.</note> had informed the Turkish Ambassador in Moscow<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d1182fn4">Selim Sarper.</note> that the Soviet Government
                    would desire soon to discuss with the Turkish Government a revision of the
                    Montreux Convention.<note n="5" xml:id="d1182fn5">Signed July 20, 1936, League
                        of Nations Treaty Series, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">clxxiii</hi>, p. 213;
                        for documentation on the interest of the United States in the Montreux
                        Conference regarding the regime of the Straits, June 22–July 20, 1936, see
                            <ref target="frus1936v03#pg_503">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1936, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, pp. 503</ref> ff.; for documentation
                        concerning discussion of the Montreux Convention at Yalta, see <ref
                            target="frus1945Malta#pg_328">
                            <hi rend="italic">Conferences at Malta and Yalta</hi>, pp.
                            328</ref>–<ref target="frus1945Malta#pg_329">329</ref>, <ref
                            target="frus1945Malta#pg_903">903</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1945Malta#pg_904">904</ref>, and <ref
                            target="frus1945Malta#pg_982">982</ref>.</note> The Turkish Ambassador
                    is said to have replied that the Montreux Convention “was an international
                    matter”.</p>
                <p>Sent Department, repeated to Moscow as No. 12.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
